div.p: Totally makes senseâ€”and youâ€™re not doing anything wrong. What youâ€™re seeing is how branches work:

li.p: When you create a branch, it starts as an identical copy of main, so youâ€™ll see the same files in both until you change something on the new branch.

For legacy pages that already exist (e.g., ai-writing-workshop.html), youâ€™re not adding a second fileâ€”youâ€™re editing the existing file on your cleanup branch so it becomes a redirect. main keeps the old version until you merge.

div.p: Hereâ€™s exactly what to do.
div.h2: 1) Make sure youâ€™re on the cleanup branch

li.p: In the repo, open the branch dropdown (top-left) and select chore/repo-cleanup-2025-09.
You should see a small pill at the top that says youâ€™re on that branch.

div.h2: 2) For pages that already exist, edit them on the cleanup branch
div.p: For each legacy path that already has a file:

li.p: Click the file (e.g., ai-writing-workshop.html).
Click the âœï¸ Edit button.
Select all and replace the entire contents with the redirect snippet (filled with the correct TARGET_URL).
In the commit box at the bottom, make sure it says â€œCommit directly to the chore/repo-cleanup-2025-09 branchâ€.
Click Commit changes.

div.p: Repeat for:

li.p: thank-you.html (unless you want a real thank-you pageâ€”happy to write one)

div.h2: 3) For folder URLs, create index.html inside the folder
div.p: If a folder already exists (e.g., EnhancedChatGPT_Simulator/), open it and:

li.p: Click Add file â†’ Create new file.
Name it EnhancedChatGPT_Simulator/index.html.
Paste the redirect snippet with the correct TARGET_URL.
Commit to your cleanup branch.

div.p: Do the same for:
div.h2: 4) Verify your changes are only on the cleanup branch

li.p: Click the Compare button (or go to Pull requests â†’ New pull request).
Base: main â† Compare: chore/repo-cleanup-2025-09.
You should see the files you edited listed as changes. That means main still has the old content, and your cleanup branch has the redirectsâ€”perfect.
Title: chore: repo cleanup + legacy redirects.
Create PR â†’ Review â†’ Merge.
After merge, main goes live with the new redirects.

hr.h2: â€œUh ohâ€”I edited on main by accidentâ€
hr.p: No panicâ€”two easy fixes:
Easiest: leave it. If the redirect files landed on main, thatâ€™s actually fine (theyâ€™ll work now). You can still do the rest of your cleanup on the branch and PR it later.
Cleaner: revert the accidental commit on main.

li.p: Go to the Commits tab on main.
Open the commit you want to undo â†’ click Revert (GitHub will create a new PR that undoes it).
Merge the revert PR.
Then re-apply that same change on the cleanup branch (edit the file there and commit).

hr.h2: How to be sure youâ€™re committing to the right branch (UI tip)
hr.p: Any time you create/edit a file, look at the commit panel at the bottom:

li.p: It should say â€œCommit directly to chore/repo-cleanup-2025-09â€.
If it says main, click â€œCommit to a new branchâ€ or switch the dropdown to your cleanup branch.

div.p: No worriesâ€”that error means the browser tried to read HTML as an SVG file. In practice, it happens if:

https://mikeguides.co/favicon.svg isnâ€™t actually your SVG (e.g., file missing â†’ Pages served an HTML 404).

div.p: Hereâ€™s the quick fix:

li.p: In your repo root, open favicon.svg.

If the first line starts with <!doctype html> or <html> or <head> or contains <link â€¦>, itâ€™s wrong.
Click the trash (Delete this file) and commit.
